          Cognitive Neuroscience and Neuropsychology

          Temporal window of integration revealed by MMN to sound omission

          Yabe, Hirooki; Tervaniemi, Mari; Reinikainen, Kalevi; Näätänen, Risto

          Author Information
          NeuroReport 8(8):p 1971-1974, May 26, 1997.

            Abstract

            THE central auditory system for event perception involves the integrating mechanism of sequential information addressed by the present study. The mismatch negativity (MMN) component of the event-related potentials (ERP) reflects the automatic detection of sound change. ERPs to occasionally omitted stimuli were measured when sequences with constant stimulus onset asynchronies (SOAs) were presented. In separate blocks, the SOA was from 100 to 350 ms. A clear MMN was elicited by a stimulus omission in a sequence of regularly spaced tone pips only when the SOA was shorter than 150 ms, yielding an estimate for the duration of the temporal window of integration used the perceptual segregation of auditory events.

            Introduction

            The mismatch negativity (MMN) component of the auditory event-related potential (ERP) is elicited by an infrequent change in homogeneous repetitive stimuli even in the absence of attention.1 This component has been described for various types of physical changes, but not reliably for complete stimulus omission.2 A response to an omitted stimulus would enable one to investigate the mechanism storing temporal information in the brain because of the absence of exogenous input.3 Many studies support the proposition4 that memory traces of previous stimuli rather than new afferent inputs are involved in MMN generation.2 An MMN to a decrement in stimulus duration5 is an example of such evidence. An MMN to a complete stimulus omission, representing the extreme case of stimulus-duration decrement, has also been looked for, in order to receive conclusive evidence for the memory-trace interpretation of MMN generation, however with very little success. Näätänen et al.6 reported that some of their subjects disclosed a small MMN type of wave to omitted stimuli in a reading condition, but these effects were not statistically significant. Further, the N2 type of the magnetoencephalographic (MEG) response to stimulus omission was reported by Joutsiniemi and Hari.7 However, the response reported by them was greater in the attended condition and generated in the frontal cortex, implying that it was not an MMN. Thus, an MMN to a complete stimulus omission in a sequence with evenly spaced stimuli has not been reliably demonstrated.

            On the other hand, several behavioural studies have reported that the central auditory system can essentially integrate successive information into meaningful entities for auditory event perception.8 For example, the prolongation of the auditory stimulus results in increased loudness, indicating temporal loudness summation.9 Furthermore, a masking stimulus following a test stimulus can erase the memory of the test stimulus only when the interval between the masking and the test stimulus is short enough.10–12 These two phenomena are traditionally considered as behavioural evidence for the temporal window of integration.13,14 However, the cortical mechanism for this integration process has not been revealed.

            The present study explored the MMN to complete stimulus omission in a sequence of evenly spaced stimuli in the view of the concept the sliding temporal window of about 200 ms in duration. If the temporal window of a given duration is initiated by each incoming stimulus, then a complete stimulus omission should elicit an MMN only when the SOA is so short as to permit each next stimulus to occur within the temporal window of integration initiated by the preceding stimulus. Conversely, if the SOA exceeds this window in duration, then stimulus omission should elicit no MMN.

            Materials and Methods

            Nine healthy adult subjects (mean age 22.2 years, range 18–25 years; five males) were studied in an electrically shielded, sound-attenuated chamber. During the experiment, the subject read a self-selected book and was instructed to ignore the auditory stimuli. Fourteen blocks of approximately 900 sinusoidal tone bursts of 1000 Hz (duration 500 ms, including 5 ms rise and fall times) were presented to the subject's left ear through earphones at an intensity of 80 dB SPL with constant SOAs. Seven different SOAs were employed in separate blocks: 100, 125, 150, 200, 250, 300 or 350 ms. At a probability of 10%, a stimulus was randomly omitted from the stimulus sequence.

            The electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded with Ag–AgCl electrodes from 10 channels. The electrode positions at the midline were Fpz, Fz, Cz and Pz. Six lateral electrodes were placed equidistantly on the coronal line connecting the mastoids through Fz. These electrodes on the left hemisphere were designated L1, L2 and LM (left mastoid), and those on the right hemisphere as R1, R2 and RM (right mastoid). The horizontal electro-oculogram (EOG) was recorded from the outer canthus of the right eye. The reference electrode was attached to the nose.

            The EEG was amplified with frequency limits of 0.1–100 Hz. The analysis period was 395 ms (sampling rate 200 Hz), including a 100 ms pre-stimulus (or pre-omission) baseline. The EEG epochs contaminated by extracerebral artifacts (amplitude change exceeding ± 150 μV) were automatically rejected. After averaging, frequencies > 30 Hz were digitally filtered out from the ERPs (FFT-filter).

            ERPs were separately averaged for omissions (moments at which the stimuli should have commenced) and for stimuli (except for those following an omission). The average number of trials was 1328 ± 150 (mean ± s.d.) for the stimuli and 147 ± 26 for the omissions.

            The mean ERP amplitudes during the period 120 ± 20 ms from the onset of the stimuli and omissions were measured. The statistical analysis was carried out by using the paired t-tests, Geisser-Greenhouse (ε) corrected analysis of variance (ANOVA) with repeated measures, and the multiple-range tests (Newman Keuls and Ryan).

            Results

            The grand-average ERPs for omissions and stimuli are presented in Fig. 1. A distinct negativity to stimulus omission (identified as MMN), commencing before the onset of the next stimulus and peaking at about 120 ms (see Box in Fig. 1), was elicited with the two shortest SOAs (100 and 125 ms) but not with any of the longer SOAs. Its scalp distribution showed a fronto-central maximum and polarity inversion at the mastoids. In contrast, no omission negativity was elicited with the longer SOAs.

            Results from a representative subject, shown in Fig. 2, showed a distinct MMN to stimulus omission with a clear polarity reversal at RM when the SOA was 100 ms (on the left) while no response could be observed to regularly presented standard stimulus (on the right).

            The scalp distribution of the present negativity was evaluated statistically. The mean amplitudes during time window 120 ± 20 ms from the beginning of omission were largest in Fz for both the 100 and 125 ms SOAs and reversed polarity in LM and RM. A repeated-measures ANOVA for these amplitudes showed statistically significant effects of the electrodes for the 100 ms (F(9,72) = 3.01, p < 0.05, ε = 0.2807: uncorrected degrees of freedom and ε-adjusted p value are presented here) and 125 ms (F(9,72) = 5.09, p < 0.02, ε = 02934) SOAs. The Ryan multiple range test on the electrodes showed a significant difference between Fz and LM, RM (p < 0.01) and between Fpz, Cz, L1, R1 and LM, RM (p < 0.05) for both 100 and 125 ms SOAs.

            Statistical comparison of the present negativity between the different SOAs was performed. The mean amplitudes during time window 120 ± 20 ms from the beginning of omission and stimulus at Fz for the different SOAs are presented in Table 1, together with the results of the two-tailed t-test for omission vs stimulus and omission vs zero. The t-test compared with zero was employed to avoid false significance produced by the responses to the stimuli. The results with the 100 and 125 ms SOAs were statistically significant in both t-tests, differing from those with the longer SOAs (see Table 1). In addition, a repeated-measures ANOVA for the amplitudes for omission showed a statistically significant effect of the SOA (F(6,48) = 3.39, p < 0.05, ε = 0.4410). A subsequent multiple range-test on the SOAs showed a significant difference between the shorter (100 and 125 ms) and longer (300 and 350 ms) SOAs (see Table 1).

            Paired t-tests in mastoids were also performed for the mean amplitudes during a short time window centering at 120 ms (120 ± 5 ms) employed for measuring the amplitudes of the small positivities with short duration. The results (one-tailed) at RM were statistically significant with the 100 ms SOA (omission vs zero: p < 0.025, omission vs stimulus: p < 0.04), and were marginally significant with the 125 ms SOA (omission vs zero: p < 0.08, omission vs stimulus: p < 0.1). No significant positivity was observed at LM with these SOAs.

            Discussion

            The present result showed a definite MMN to a complete stimulus omission. This component was identified as MMN on the following grounds. First, this component was elicited by a change in a repetitive auditory event. Second, it was an attention-independent component, obtained in an ignore condition. Third, the scalp distribution of the negativity showed a fronto-central maximum and polarity reversal in mastoid recordings with nose reference, differing from that of the N2b related to attentive processes.15 Such an inverted polarity over the Sylvian fissure toward the mastoids has already been confirmed for MMNs to a change of frequency, intensity, duration16 and locus of spacial origin of the stimulus.17 In addition, the present negativity is not an artifact of some overlapping response to the preceding stimuli for: (1) with short SOAs, with which this negativity occurred, the stimulus elicited activity was in general of very low amplitude due to refractoriness (see the thin line at Fz in Fig. 1); (2) this negativity cannot be an enlarged response to the stimulus presented after the prolonged interval due to omission, because it commenced before the stimulus following omission; (3) the N1 and P2 components to the preceding stimulus can be distinguished from the present negativity both in latency and scalp distribution, the N1-P2 being largest at Cz and this negativity at Fz.

            According to Näätänen18 there are, in principle, two alternative hypotheses by which MMN elicitation can be interpreted. One is to assume that the MMN is generated by new afferent elements responding to the deviant stimuli. The other possibility is to assume that MMN reflects stimulus change found in a comparison process between the deviant event and the memory trace formed by the repetitive stimulus. The MMN elicitation by stimulus omission demonstrated by the present study, in itself, provides strong evidence for the memory trace hypothesis because, obviously, no afferent neurones could be activated by the physically absent stimulus.

            In the following, theoretical interpretations of the present omission MMN will be considered. Previous ERP studies of stimulus omission3,6,7 have suggested that omission might be detected by a hypothetical timer checking the regularity of stimuli. According to this hypothesis, the negativity reflects the failure of the stimulus to occur at the regular time kept in the hypothetical timer of sensory memory. The hypothetical timer, however, cannot account for the present results since no MMN was elicited by stimulus omission with the longer SOAs used, although these were still very short (≥ 150 ms).

            This dependence of the present omission negativity on the length of the SOA can be explained with the postulated temporal window of integration2,13,14 shown in Fig. 3. According to this hypothesis, if two stimuli are presented in close succession, then the second stimulus enters the system within a period during which the integration process initiated by the onset of the first stimulus still is in progress, that is, during the window of integration. Therefore what was represented as the standard event by the memory trace was not a single stimulus but rather a compound stimulus or vent with a short temporal gap between its two parts. Thus, on this hypothesis, the compound vs single stimulus nature of the representation developed during repeated stimulus presentation determines whether stimulus omission elicits an MMN or not.

            Conclusion

            The present results showed a definite MMN to stimulus omission when the constant SOA was < 150 ms, whereas no MMN was elicited when the SOA was prolonged to 200 ms. This SOA dependence of the omission response can be explained with the postulated temporal window of integration suggesting that if stimuli are presented in close succession, then the second of two consecutive stimuli enter the central auditory system during the window of integration (of about 150–170 ms) initiated by the first stimulus.

            General Summary

            A deviation in the form of an omission from the acoustic environment activates an automatic, pre-attentive change detection system in the human brain based on a memory mechanism that builds a neural trace representing the preceding sounds. The present study revealed that the brain mechanisms underlying this short-term sensory memory integrate temporally acoustic events up to 200 ms for unitary auditory event perception.
